article.description:
Diana Taurasi scored 18 points to lift the
Phoenix Mercury over the Seattle Storm 63-55 on Saturday night for their third straight win after the monthlong Olympic break.
article.headline: Taurasi's 18 points help Mercury stay hot
article.linkText: Hot and cold: Mercury keep winning, Storm keep losing
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Behind 18 points each from Diana Taurasi and
Penny Taylor, the Phoenix Mercury kept their playoff hopes alive by
knocking off the second-place team in the Western Conference.

The Mercury, the worst team in the WNBA last season, beat the
Seattle Storm 63-55 on Saturday night.

Seattle (17-11) trails first-place Los Angeles by four games.
Phoenix (15-13) moved into a fourth-place tie with Sacramento with
six games to play. The top four teams of each conference advance to
the playoffs.

Sue Bird and Kamila Vodichkova scored 12 points apiece for
Seattle, which has lost three straight without league MVP and
leading scorer Lauren Jackson. She is on the injured list with a
sprained right foot and visiting her ill grandmother in Australia.

The Mercury have won three straight since the monthlong Olympic
break, and seven of eight games since July 21. The Storm have lost three in a row since the break. Seattle had won seven of eight before the hiatus.

Taurasi scored 11 points during a key second-half stretch and
added seven assists and six rebounds.

The Mercury won despite missing 11 of their first 15 shots and
trailing 22-12.

"That's showing that we're getting better," Taurasi said.
"When we can win ugly."

The Storm arrived in Phoenix just four hours before tipoff
because of flight delays over security issues at Los Angeles
International Airport.

"There's no doubt it takes its toll," Seattle coach Anne
Donovan said. "But that's what this league is all about. You have
got to be able to overcome that, mentally and physically be able to
overcome days like we had today."

Phoenix went on an 18-7 run to take a 54-48 lead with 4:19 left,
taking advantage of Seattle's poor free-throw shooting. The Storm
missed 6-of-8 during that stretch, and finished 16-for-23 from the
line.

"Free throws you should always be knocking down," Donovan
said. "It's free money. It's concentration, it's about getting a
deep breath and blocking out the fatigue. "
